\begin_layout Itemize
On a given day, we are doing quality control at a factory that produces
 light bulbs 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We are interested in how long these bulbs last on average 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The population consists of 
\series bold
all the bulbs
\series default
 that the factory produces 
\series bold
that day
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To get an idea about the duration of the bulbs, we randomly take a few and
 see how long it takes before they run out 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Obviously, we are not going to try all the bulbs! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will try to say something about the population of 
\series bold
all
\series default
 bulbs produced that day, using the observations in our 
\series bold
sample
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That is called 
\series bold
statistical inference
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


