Bulbs: population versus sample
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the duration for a light bulb produced on the day we are testing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If we would test 
\series bold
all
\series default
 the bulbs, we would 
\series bold
know
\series default
 the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $E[X]=\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 for our 
\series bold
population
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We only have a 
\series bold
sample
\series default
 of all light bulbs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The number 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{X}$
\end_inset

 exists, but we do not know it! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Instead, we look at the 
\series bold
sample average
\series default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\size larger
The sample average is a random variable!
\series default
 
\end_layout

